<paragraph blockId="3.[188,1399,777,944]" box="[234,298,777,803]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[234,298,777,803]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">Male</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[188,1399,777,944]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">
ADULT HABITUS (
<figureCitation box="[376,520,812,838]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[189,232,1927,1953]" captionTargetBox="[211,1367,329,1876]" captionTargetId="figure-16@2.[189,1398,310,1889]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. Tibetisoperla elongata sp. nov. A. ♂, holotype (HIST), habitus, dorsal view. B. ♀, paratype (HIST), habitus, dorsal view. C. ♂, holotype (HIST), head and pronotum, dorsal view. D. ♂, holotype (HIST), terga 3–9, dorsal view. Abbreviations: see Material and methods." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6658615" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6658615/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">Figs 1A, 1C</figureCitation>
). Forewing length 
<quantity box="[744,888,811,838]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.3" metricValueMax="8.5" metricValueMin="8.1" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" unit="mm" value="8.3" valueMax="8.5" valueMin="8.1">8.1–8.5 mm</quantity>
, hindwing length 7.0– 
<quantity box="[1148,1237,812,838]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.2" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" unit="mm" value="7.2">7.2 mm</quantity>
(N=3). Head brown with dark brown arween ocelli and tentorial callosities. M-line dark brown. Triocellate, anterior ocellus smaller. Antennae brownish, scape brown, palpi brownish. Pronotum disc with large area of brown to dark brown rugosities and pale medial stripe. Legs brownish. Wings hyaline, veins brown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[189,1399,983,1220]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">
ABDOMEN (
<figureCitation box="[319,421,983,1009]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[189,232,1927,1953]" captionTargetBox="[211,1367,329,1876]" captionTargetId="figure-16@2.[189,1398,310,1889]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. Tibetisoperla elongata sp. nov. A. ♂, holotype (HIST), habitus, dorsal view. B. ♀, paratype (HIST), habitus, dorsal view. C. ♂, holotype (HIST), head and pronotum, dorsal view. D. ♂, holotype (HIST), terga 3–9, dorsal view. Abbreviations: see Material and methods." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6658615" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6658615/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">Figs 1D</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[437,453,983,1009]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="4.[189,232,1891,1917]" captionTargetBox="[307,1290,306,1798]" captionTargetId="figure-15@4.[287,1300,265,1852]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="Fig. 2. Tibetisoperla elongata sp. nov., ♂, holotype (HIST). A. Terminalia, dorsal view. B. Terminalia, ventral view. C. Vesicle, ventral view. D. Vesicle, lateral view. E. Terminalia, lateral view. F. Tergum 10 and paraproct, dorsal view. G. Apex of tergum 10 and paraproct, lateral view (cercus removed). Abbreviations: see Material and methods." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6658617" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6658617/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">2</figureCitation>
). Abdominal terga brownish and terga 1–4 darkly sclerotized. Terga 2–9 each with a pair of small dark spots medially and dark medial strip (obscure in young individual). Tergum 9 bearing two paramedial patches of sensilla on darker posterior margin, patches separated by pale T-shaped mesal membrane. Tergum 10 bilobate, distally upcurved with 3–4 thick apical setae. Vesicle located on posterior margin of sternum 8, generally tongue-shaped, ca almost as long as its width, basally brown but apex paler, covered with hairs. Paraprocts sclerotized, with partially separated apical sclerite covered by small terminal spines.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[189,1399,1259,1321]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">
AEDEAGUS (
<figureCitation box="[324,395,1259,1285]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="5.[189,232,1928,1954]" captionTargetBox="[216,1368,461,1858]" captionTargetId="figure-69@5.[196,1392,451,1884]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="Fig. 3. Tibetisoperla elongata sp. nov., ♂, holotype (HIST). A. Aedeagus, dorsal view. B. ♂, Aedeagus, ventral view. C. Aedeagus, lateral view. D. Basal half of aedeagus, detail of spinous area, dorsal view. E. Aedeagal apex, dorsal view. Abbreviations: see Material and methods." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6658621" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6658621/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">Fig. 3</figureCitation>
). Membranous except for a v-shaped ventrobasal sclerite, tubular and slightly curved ventrally at apex, mostly covered by fine spinules, dorsoapical and ventroapical portions bald.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[189,1399,1360,1457]" box="[234,326,1360,1386]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[234,326,1360,1386]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">Female</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[189,1399,1360,1457]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">
ADULT HABITUS (
<figureCitation box="[379,470,1395,1421]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[189,232,1927,1953]" captionTargetBox="[211,1367,329,1876]" captionTargetId="figure-16@2.[189,1398,310,1889]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. Tibetisoperla elongata sp. nov. A. ♂, holotype (HIST), habitus, dorsal view. B. ♀, paratype (HIST), habitus, dorsal view. C. ♂, holotype (HIST), head and pronotum, dorsal view. D. ♂, holotype (HIST), terga 3–9, dorsal view. Abbreviations: see Material and methods." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6658615" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6658615/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">Fig. 1B</figureCitation>
). Forewing length 9.0– 
<quantity box="[747,840,1395,1422]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="9.9" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" unit="mm" value="9.9">9.9 mm</quantity>
, hindwing length 
<quantity box="[1052,1196,1395,1422]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.05" metricValueMax="8.2" metricValueMin="7.9" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" unit="mm" value="8.05" valueMax="8.2" valueMin="7.9">7.9–8.2 mm</quantity>
. Body coloration similar to male.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[189,1398,1496,1557]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">
ABDOMEN (
<figureCitation box="[322,401,1496,1522]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="6.[189,232,1928,1954]" captionTargetBox="[241,1339,368,1878]" captionTargetId="figure-16@6.[201,1386,330,1891]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="Fig. 4. Tibetisoperla elongata sp. nov., ♀, paratype (HIST) A. Head and pronotum, dorsal view. B. Terminalia, dorsal view. C. Terminalia, ventral view. D. Subgenital plate, lateral view. E. Subgenital plate, ventral view. Abbreviations: see Material and methods." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6658623" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6658623/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). Tergum 10 unmodified. Subgenital plate sclerotized and subquadrate, produced posteriorly covering anterior half of sternum 9, with a broad arcuate posteromedial notch.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[189,375,1596,1623]" box="[189,375,1596,1623]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">EGG. Unknown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="128" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="3.[189,344,1662,1688]" box="[189,344,1662,1688]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,344,1662,1688]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,344,1662,1688]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">Distribution</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[189,1399,1708,1770]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">
<collectingCountry box="[189,264,1708,1734]" name="China" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">China</collectingCountry>
: 
<collectingRegion box="[275,486,1708,1734]" country="China" name="Qinghai" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">Qinghai Province</collectingRegion>
. Presently only known from two sites along the riverside of Daitong River in Menyuan County.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="130" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[189,304,1809,1835]" box="[189,304,1809,1835]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">
<heading bold="true" box="[189,304,1809,1835]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,304,1809,1835]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="3.[189,1400,1855,2023]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">
The type species of 
<emphasis box="[432,597,1855,1881]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Huo &amp; Du" authorityYear="2021" box="[432,592,1855,1881]" class="Insecta" family="Perlodidae" genus="Tibetisoperla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Tibetisoperla</taxonomicName>
,
</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Huo &amp; Du, 2021" authorityName="Huo &amp; Du" authorityYear="2021" box="[605,970,1855,1882]" class="Insecta" family="Perlodidae" genus="Tibetisoperla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wangluyui">
<emphasis box="[605,759,1855,1881]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">T. wangluyui</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Huo Q. B. &amp; Du Y. Z." box="[767,970,1856,1882]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" pagination="343 - 352" refId="ref3577" refString="Huo Q. B. &amp; Du Y. Z. 2021. A new genus of Isoperline (Plecoptera: Perlodidae) from Tibet, China. Zootaxa 4996 (2): 343 - 352. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4996.2.8" type="journal article" year="2021">Huo &amp; Du, 2021</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
is a dark species and has a reduced vesicle on sternum 8, but the new species is a brownish species and has a developed vesicle which is present in typical 
<taxonomicName authority="Banks, 1906" authorityName="Banks" authorityYear="1906" box="[439,699,1926,1952]" class="Insecta" family="Perlodidae" genus="Isoperla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[439,538,1926,1952]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">Isoperla</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Banks N." box="[548,699,1926,1952]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" pagination="174 - 175" refId="ref3377" refString="Banks N. 1906. On the perlid genus Chloroperla. Entomological News 17: 174 - 175." type="journal article" year="1906">Banks, 1906</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Teslenko V. A. &amp; Zhiltzova L. A." box="[717,1054,1926,1952]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" refId="ref3825" refString="Teslenko V. A. &amp; Zhiltzova L. A. 2009. Key to the Stoneflies (Insecta, Plecoptera) of Russia and Adjacent Countries. Imagines and Nymphs. Russian Academy of Sciences, Far Eastern Branch, Dalnauka, Vladivostok." type="book" year="2009">Teslenko &amp; Zhiltzova 2009</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Muranyi D." box="[1069,1242,1926,1952]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" pagination="1 - 46" refId="ref3743" refString="Muranyi D. 2011. Balkanian species of the genus Isoperla Banks, 1906 (Plecoptera: Perlodidae). Zootaxa 3049: 1 - 46. https: // doi. org / 10.1643 / CE- 08 - 219" type="journal article" year="2011">Murányi 2011</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Szczytko S. W. &amp; Kondratieff B. C." pageId="3" pageNumber="128" pagination="1 - 289" refId="ref3783" refString="Szczytko S. W. &amp; Kondratieff B. C. 2015. A Review of the Eastern Nearctic Isoperlinae (Plecoptera: Perlodidae) with the description of twenty-two new species. Monographs of Illiesia 1: 1 - 289." type="journal article" year="2015">Szczytko &amp; Kondratieff 2015</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Cao Z. S. &amp; Wang Y. &amp; Li W. H." box="[411,602,1961,1987]" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" pagination="251 - 260" refId="ref3421" refString="Cao Z. S., Wang Y. &amp; Li W. H. 2020. A new species of Isoperla (Plecoptera: Perlodidae) from China. Zootaxa 4858 (2): 251 - 260. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 4858.2.6" type="journal article" year="2020">
Cao 
<emphasis box="[470,532,1961,1987]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">et al.</emphasis>
2020
</bibRefCitation>
), another genus of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Frison" authorityYear="1942" box="[833,963,1961,1987]" class="Insecta" family="Perlodidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Isoperlinae">Isoperlinae</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry box="[1006,1080,1961,1987]" name="China" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">China</collectingCountry>
. However, the large apical setae of tergum 10 and spiny apical sclerite of paraproct clearly show its placement in 
<emphasis box="[1203,1367,1996,2022]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="128">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Huo &amp; Du" authorityYear="2021" box="[1203,1363,1996,2022]" class="Insecta" family="Perlodidae" genus="Tibetisoperla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="128" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Tibetisoperla</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<caption ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6658617" ID-Zenodo-Dep="6658617" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6658617/files/figure.png" pageId="4" pageNumber="129" startId="4.[189,232,1891,1917]" targetBox="[307,1290,306,1798]" targetPageId="4">
<paragraph blockId="4.[189,1399,1891,2024]" pageId="4" pageNumber="129">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,268,1891,1917]" pageId="4" pageNumber="129">Fig. 2.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Yan &amp; Chen &amp; Bozdoğan, 2022" authorityName="Yan &amp; Chen &amp; Bozdoğan" authorityYear="2022" box="[275,544,1891,1917]" class="Insecta" family="Perlodidae" genus="Tibetisoperla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="4" pageNumber="129" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elongata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[275,544,1891,1917]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="129">Tibetisoperla elongata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[551,645,1892,1918]" pageId="4" pageNumber="129" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, ♂, holotype (HIST). 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[904,925,1891,1917]" pageId="4" pageNumber="129">A</emphasis>
. Terminalia, dorsal view. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1231,1250,1892,1918]" pageId="4" pageNumber="129">B</emphasis>
. Terminalia, ventral view. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[352,372,1926,1952]" pageId="4" pageNumber="129">C</emphasis>
. Vesicle, ventral view. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[651,672,1927,1953]" pageId="4" pageNumber="129">D</emphasis>
. Vesicle, lateral view. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[942,962,1927,1953]" pageId="4" pageNumber="129">E</emphasis>
. Terminalia, lateral view. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[1276,1292,1927,1953]" pageId="4" pageNumber="129">F</emphasis>
. Tergum 10 and paraproct, dorsal view. 
<emphasis bold="true" box="[567,590,1962,1988]" pageId="4" pageNumber="129">G</emphasis>
. Apex of tergum 10 and paraproct, lateral view (cercus removed). Abbreviations: see Material and methods.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph blockId="5.[188,1399,265,397]" pageId="5" pageNumber="130">
The female of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yan &amp; Chen &amp; Bozdoğan" authorityYear="2022" box="[357,491,265,291]" class="Insecta" family="Perlodidae" genus="Tibetisoperla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elongata">
<emphasis box="[357,491,265,291]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="130">T. elongata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is different to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Huo &amp; Du" authorityYear="2021" box="[659,811,265,291]" class="Insecta" family="Perlodidae" genus="Tibetisoperla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="wangluyui">
<emphasis box="[659,811,265,291]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="130">T. wangluyui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in subgenital plate structure, the former is broadly semicircular while the latter is subquadrate. Additionally, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yan &amp; Chen &amp; Bozdoğan" authorityYear="2022" box="[882,1017,300,326]" class="Insecta" family="Perlodidae" genus="Tibetisoperla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elongata">
<emphasis box="[882,1017,300,326]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="130">T. elongata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with a typically posterior notch which is indistinct of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yan &amp; Chen &amp; Bozdoğan" authorityYear="2022" box="[440,585,335,361]" class="Insecta" family="Perlodidae" genus="Tibetisoperla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sclerotica">
<emphasis box="[440,585,335,361]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="130">T. sclerotica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Terga 1–8 of female with black medial stripes and subgenital plate is broadly triangular in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Yan &amp; Chen &amp; Bozdoğan" authorityYear="2022" box="[437,583,370,396]" class="Insecta" family="Perlodidae" genus="Tibetisoperla" higherTaxonomySource="CoL,GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Plecoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="130" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sclerotica">
<emphasis box="[437,583,370,396]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="130">T. sclerotica</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
